, a variant of   Gard  , with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Compare also   Alligood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leggett","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>legat</i>, <i>legate</i> ‘delegate, ambassador, deputy’ (Old French <i>legat</i>), Latin <i>legatus</i> ‘one who is appointed or ordained’.","English: variant of   Legard  , especially in Sussex, perhaps through confusion of the two names."]},{"name":"Gard","meanings":["English (southern): occupational name from Middle English <i>gard(e)</i>, <i>guard(e)</i> ‘care, custody, protection’ (Old French <i>garde</i> ‘guard, watchman’), for a member of a town watch or troop of guards.","Norwegian (also <b>Gård</b>): habitational name from any of the two farmsteads so named in Rogaland, from Old Norse <i>garthr</i> ‘farm’.","Swedish (<b>Gård</b>): topographic or ornamental name from <i>gård</i> ‘farm’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Legard was born about 1206, in Long Riston, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Legard about 1232. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1206–":"umbes 1206–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1242–1305":"1242–1305","1342–1405":"1342–1405","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1242":"1242","Abt 1235":"umbes 1235","Abt 1206":"umbes 1206","1206":"1206","1305":"1305","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","Abt 1233":"